     9	
    10	# System Deep Loop
    11	
    12	One skill, five active workflow families, one nested runtime layer. `system-deep-loop` is the public, advisor-routable home for active deep-loop personas; `runtime/` is the frozen, MCP-free infrastructure layer it consumes (formerly the separate `deep-loop-runtime` skill, merged into this hub 2026-07-08). This hub holds NO per-mode convergence, state, or synthesis logic — each active mode keeps its own contract in its packet, and the hub only routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json`.
    13	
    14	Use `@context` for one-shot retrieval, `/deep:research` for iterative investigation with a bounded context snapshot, `/deep:review` for iterative audit with a bounded review snapshot, `/deep:alignment` for read-only-by-default conformance against a named standard authority, or `/speckit:plan` for implementation planning.
    15	
    16	---
    17	
    18	## 1. WHEN TO USE
    19	
    20	Use this skill (through the hub) for any active deep-loop workflow. Invoke it as `Skill(system-deep-loop)` (optionally with a mode hint such as `research: <request>` or `alignment: <request>`); the hub classifies the request, resolves a `workflowMode`, and loads the matching nested mode packet. Active `/deep:*` commands and native agent types remain as complementary surfaces over the same packets.
    21	
    22	| Mode | Use it for | Packet | Command | Agent |
    23	|------|-----------|--------|---------|-------|
    24	| **research** | Outward, web + code iterative investigation → `research/research.md` | `system-deep-loop/deep-research/` | `/deep:research` | `deep-research` |
    25	| **review** | Iterative review loop → P0/P1/P2 findings + verdict | `system-deep-loop/deep-review/` | `/deep:review` | `deep-review` |
    26	| **ai-council** | Multi-seat planning deliberation → `ai-council/**` artifacts | `system-deep-loop/deep-ai-council/` | `/deep:ai-council` | `ai-council` |
    27	| **improvement** (3 lanes) | Evaluator-first improvement: `agent-improvement`, `model-benchmark`, `skill-benchmark` | `system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/` | `/deep:agent-improvement` · `/deep:model-benchmark` · `/deep:skill-benchmark` | `deep-improvement` |
    28	| **alignment** | Read-only-by-default conformance audit against a named standard authority | `system-deep-loop/deep-alignment/` | `/deep:alignment` | `deep-alignment` |
    29	
    30	### When NOT to Use
    31	- A single quick read/edit (no loop) — use the relevant code or doc skill directly.
    32	- Backend/runtime support (executor, coverage-graph, scoring, fan-out) — that is `runtime/`, consumed here, not invoked as a user workflow (formerly the separate deep-loop-runtime skill).
    33	
    34	---
    35	
    36	## 2. SMART ROUTING
    37	
    38	Routing is **registry-driven** (invokable-hub, Option E). `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub reads it and does not re-derive the mapping. When invoked as `Skill(system-deep-loop[, "<mode>: <request>"])`, the hub classifies the request to a `workflowMode`, resolves it through the registry, and loads `registry[mode].packet`. The advisor routes any deep-loop query to the single identity `system-deep-loop`; the hub then picks the mode. The `/deep:*` commands and native agent types remain as complementary surfaces — they reach the same packets through static routers/agent definitions — and the hub holds NO per-mode logic.
    39	
    40	> **Compiled routing (opt-in, flag-gated, additive).** When `SPECKIT_COMPILED_ROUTING=1`, resolve the mode via the compiled router contract first:
    41	> ```bash
    42	> node .opencode/bin/compiled-route.cjs --hub system-deep-loop --prompt "<task>"
    43	> ```
    44	> Follow the returned decision — `route` (use its `targets`), `clarify`/`defer` (disambiguate), `reject` (refuse). On a `{"servingAuthority":"legacy"}` sentinel or any error, use the routing below. The front door self-gates on serving-authority, and the flag is **off by default**, so this is inert until compiled routing is activated for `system-deep-loop`.
    45	
    46	This hub is an intent/registry router, not a keyed resource-discovery router: at runtime it omits `discover_markdown_resources` and only guards registry-selected packet loads, never selecting hub-level `references/<key>/` or `assets/<key>/` resources by runtime key. It does carry a second-layer surface router at `shared/references/smart-routing.md` — a benchmark/replay artifact (mirroring sk-prompt/sk-code) that maps a resolved mode's intent to packet-qualified child leaves so router-replay can emit canonical `{workflowMode, leafResourceId}` typed pairs against `leaf-manifest.json`. That surface layer never re-decides the mode and is not a runtime hub discovery surface; the hub still routes by `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json` alone.
    47	
    48	### Note on the frontmatter `allowed-tools` grant
    49	
    50	The hub's own routing logic is read-only (classify, guard a path, load a packet). The frontmatter `allowed-tools` list is nonetheless broad because, per the two-axis hub canon contract, a hub's tool grant MUST equal the exact union of every registered mode's `toolSurface.allowed` in `mode-registry.json` — not the tool set the hub's own logic uses. This is a hard invariant enforced by `parent-skill-check.cjs` (check 3j: "hub allowed-tools equals the union of mode tool surfaces"); narrowing the frontmatter grant to only what routing-only logic needs would fail that check and break every mode whose `toolSurface` isn't a subset of the narrowed list. Treat the breadth of `allowed-tools` as evidence of the child modes' combined needs, not of mutating logic living in the hub.
    51	
    52	### The three-tier discriminator
    53	- **`workflowMode`** — the public active mode key: `research`, `review`, `ai-council`, `alignment`, and the three improvement lanes `agent-improvement`, `model-benchmark`, `skill-benchmark`.
    54	- **`runtimeLoopType`** — the graph-backed convergence key consumed by `runtime/scripts/convergence.cjs` (validated against active `research|review|council`). **Explicit `null` for all three improvement lanes; never inferred from `workflowMode`.** Note `ai-council` maps to `runtimeLoopType: council`, while `alignment` maps to `runtimeLoopType: review`.
    55	- **`backendKind`** — which backend runs the mode: `runtime-loop-type` (research/review/ai-council/alignment) or `improvement-host` (`deep-improvement/scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode`).
    56	
    57	### Routing rule
    58	```
    59	classify the request to a workflowMode (dominant deep-loop intent; mode hint like "research: ..." overrides)
    60	guard mode-registry.json inside SKILL_ROOT and read it as data
    61	if classifier confidence is low or no mode dominates:
    62	  → return UNKNOWN_FALLBACK with a disambiguation checklist: choose research, review, ai-council, alignment, or one improvement lane
    63	else:
    64	  → resolve workflowMode from the hint / classified intent (or the /deep:* command / advisor alias)
    65	  → find registry[mode]; if missing, return UNKNOWN_FALLBACK instead of loading a guessed path
    66	  → guard registry[mode].packet/SKILL.md inside SKILL_ROOT and load it only if the packet directory and SKILL.md both exist
    67	       e.g. registry["research"].packet → system-deep-loop/deep-research/SKILL.md
    68	       e.g. registry["alignment"].packet → system-deep-loop/deep-alignment/SKILL.md
    69	       (the 3 improvement modes all share the system-deep-loop/deep-improvement/ packet)
    70	  → if registry[mode].runtimeLoopType !== null: backend = convergence.cjs --loop-type <runtimeLoopType>
    71	     else: backend = improvement loop-host (--mode), per backendKind
    72	```
    73	
    74	Router-driven loads MUST use `_guard_in_skill(relative_path)` before `load()`, reject paths that escape this skill or do not end in `.md`, and check `if packet_base.exists()` plus `if packet_skill.exists()` before loading. The fallback must name the unresolved `workflowMode` when known, avoid loading any guessed packet, and ask the operator to provide one of the registered modes or the matching `/deep:*` command.
    75	
    76	Intent classification favors the single dominant active deep-loop mode; a mode hint (`research: ...`, `review: ...`, `ai-council: ...`, `alignment: ...`, or an improvement lane) overrides the classifier. The legacy advisor projection maps stay hardcoded and drift-guarded against the registry, and the command files remain static routers with hardcoded asset/mode routing; neither resolves from `mode-registry.json` at runtime, but both stay equal to its projection.
    77	
    78	Per-mode behavior is **not flattened**: each active packet keeps its own convergence math, state shape, artifacts, and tool-permission guards (research has WebFetch; review/ai-council are code/inward-only; alignment is a named-standard, read-only-by-default conformance audit; improvement is the only direct mutation family). Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` — this hub's — is preserved, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill identity regardless of which surface (hub `Skill()`, `/deep:*` command, or agent) reaches a mode.
    79	
    80	---
    81	
    82	## 3. HOW IT WORKS
    83	
    84	### Layout
    85	```
    86	system-deep-loop/
    87	  SKILL.md               # this routing hub (no per-mode logic)
    88	  mode-registry.json     # the three-tier discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)
    89	  graph-metadata.json    # the ONE advisor identity for the whole skill
    90	  deep-research/   deep-review/   deep-ai-council/   deep-improvement/   deep-alignment/   # active mode packets
    91	  shared/synthesis/      # workflows-shared synthesis (e.g. emitResourceMap)
    92	```
    93	
    94	Each active mode packet keeps its own `SKILL.md`, `references/`, `scripts/`, `assets/`, `feature-catalog/`, or `manual-testing-playbook/` as applicable, with internal paths repointed and **no per-packet `graph-metadata.json`** — only this hub carries one, so the advisor discovers exactly one skill. The `deep-ai-council` packet folder follows the standard `folder == packetSkillName` convention (`deep-ai-council`); its legacy public surfaces (the `/deep:ai-council` command and the `ai-council` agent) intentionally keep the shorter `ai-council` key, so always resolve the packet path through `mode-registry.json` rather than hardcoding it.
    95	
    96	### Backend
    97	All modes consume `runtime/` (frozen, MCP-free): executor config, prompt-pack, validation, atomic state, coverage-graph, Bayesian scoring, fan-out, the council primitives, and the promoted plumbing (capability resolver, artifact-root, loop-lock CLI, lifecycle taxonomy). The runtime never gains an `improvement` loopType — improvement stays host-driven.
    98	
    99	---
   100	
   101	## 4. RULES
   102	
   103	### ✅ ALWAYS
   104	- **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json` (read the `packet` key; never hardcode a router mapping or packet path in the hub).
   105	- **ALWAYS** keep advisor projection maps hardcoded and drift-guarded against the registry; command mode routing is still hardcoded in the command files and does not resolve through `mode-registry.json`.
   106	- **ALWAYS** keep each mode's convergence/state/artifact contract in its packet — the hub stays logic-free.
   107	- **ALWAYS** keep exactly one `graph-metadata.json` (this hub's) so the advisor sees one skill identity, whether a mode is reached via `Skill(system-deep-loop)`, a `/deep:*` command, or an agent.
   108	- **ALWAYS** keep `Skill(system-deep-loop)` hub routing, the `/deep:*` commands, and the agent types as complementary surfaces over the same packets — never let one surface fork per-mode logic out of its packet.
   109	
   110	### ⛔ NEVER
   111	- **NEVER** add an `improvement` `loopType` to `runtime/convergence.cjs` (improvement is host-driven; `runtimeLoopType` stays `null`).
   112	- **NEVER** infer `runtimeLoopType` from `workflowMode` — read it from the registry (explicit `null` is load-bearing).
   113	- **NEVER** let a read-only mode (research/review/ai-council/alignment) reach the improvement mutation scripts (`promote-candidate.cjs`/`rollback-candidate.cjs`).
   114	- **NEVER** add a `graph-metadata.json` or a discoverable skill marker inside a mode packet or `shared/`.
   115	
   116	### ⚠️ ESCALATE IF
   117	- A new mode is needed beyond the seven registered — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet, do not bolt logic onto the hub.
   118	- A change would require the runtime to gain MCP tools or an improvement loopType — that contradicts the architecture; escalate.
   119	
   120	---
   121	
   122	## 5. REFERENCES
   123	
   124	- Backend: `.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/runtime/` (frozen, consumed by every mode; nested infrastructure, not a separate skill).
   125	- Mode packets: `deep-research/SKILL.md`, `deep-review/SKILL.md`, `deep-ai-council/SKILL.md`, `deep-improvement/SKILL.md`, `deep-alignment/SKILL.md` (per-mode detail).
   126	- Commands: the active `/deep:*` commands under `.opencode/commands/deep/` (complementary surface).
   127	- Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract — the authoritative `packet` paths).
   128	
   129	---
   130	
   131	## 6. SUCCESS CRITERIA
   132	
   133	- The hub resolves one primary active `workflowMode` for the request through `mode-registry.json` (improvement folds to the right lane via the registry, never by array order).
   134	- The selected mode packet owns the detailed convergence/state/artifact workflow; the hub stayed routing-only.
   135	- `Skill(system-deep-loop[, hint])` reaches a mode, and the `/deep:*` commands and agent types still reach the same packets.
   136	- Exactly one `graph-metadata.json` exists for the whole skill; no packet carries its own.
   137	
   138	---
   139	
   140	## 7. INTEGRATION POINTS
   141	
   142	### Modes
   143	- `research` — outward web + code iterative investigation (`research/research.md`).
   144	- `review` — iterative review loop, P0/P1/P2 findings + verdict.
   145	- `ai-council` — multi-seat planning deliberation (`ai-council/**` artifacts).
   146	- `improvement` (3 lanes) — evaluator-first agent/model/skill improvement.
   147	- `alignment` — read-only-by-default conformance audit against a named standard authority (`alignment/` artifacts).
   148	
   149	### Surfaces and Consumers
   150	- `Skill(system-deep-loop)` is the invokable hub; active `/deep:*` commands and the agent types (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `ai-council`, `deep-improvement`, `deep-alignment`) are complementary surfaces over the same packets.
   151	- `runtime/` is the frozen, MCP-free backend every mode consumes (nested infrastructure, not a separate skill).
   152	- `/speckit:plan` consumes `@context` packages plus research/review/alignment outputs; spec-folder docs consume research/review/alignment output.
   153	
   154	---
   155	
