.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:229:Honor whichever dimensions the user names. Model stays on `gpt-5.5` and service tier stays on `fast` unless the user explicitly names a different model or tier; keep the reasoning effort within the chosen model's ceiling (defined in the roster below).
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:233:`gpt-5.5` at `medium` is the skill default for cross-AI delegation. Four GPT models are callable on the `fast` service tier via `--model`; each caps at a different reasoning-effort ceiling. Pick the model for the task, then tune reasoning effort within that model's ceiling. All are `-c service_tier="fast"`.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:238:| **GPT-5.6 LUNA** | `gpt-5.6-luna` | `low` · `medium` · `high` · `xhigh` · `max` | Implementation-heavy work wanting deeper reasoning; the `luna-impl` profile pins `max`. |
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:239:| **GPT-5.6 TERRA** | `gpt-5.6-terra` | `low` · `medium` · `high` · `xhigh` · `max` | A GPT-5.6 fast sibling; callable directly via `-m gpt-5.6-terra` (no dedicated config profile). |
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:240:| **GPT-5.6 SOL** | `gpt-5.6-sol` | `low` · `medium` · `high` · `xhigh` · `max` · `ultra` | Verification / review and the hardest planning — the only model reaching `ultra`; the `sol-verify` profile pins `xhigh`. |
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:242:**Reasoning-effort scale** (ascending): `none` · `minimal` · `low` · `medium` (5.5 default) · `high` · `xhigh` · `max` · `ultra`. Ceilings per model: `gpt-5.5` ≤ `xhigh`; `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-terra` ≤ `max`; `gpt-5.6-sol` ≤ `ultra`. Set effort with `-c model_reasoning_effort="<level>"` (there is **no `--reasoning-effort` flag**).
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:244:**Selection Strategy**: default `gpt-5.5 medium`; raise to `high` / `xhigh` for architecture, security, and complex planning; escalate to a GPT-5.6 model when the task wants reasoning past `xhigh` — `gpt-5.6-luna max` for implementation, `gpt-5.6-sol xhigh` / `ultra` for verification and review; drop to `low` / `minimal` for trivial lookups. Per-task rationale table: [cli-reference.md](./references/cli-reference.md) §5.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:248:The calling AI is the conductor; Codex profiles in `.codex/config.toml` `[profiles.<name>]` shape HOW Codex processes the task (sandbox, reasoning). Route with `-p <name>` when the task matches a specialization. Full roster and invocation patterns: [agent-delegation.md](./references/agent-delegation.md).
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:259:Git diff review uses the built-in subcommand (no `-p`): `codex exec review "..." --commit HEAD`. Profiles may override `model`, `model_reasoning_effort`, `sandbox_mode`, `approval_policy`. The `.codex/agents/*.toml` files define personas for the interactive multi-agent TUI, NOT the `-p` flag.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:268:- **No `--reasoning-effort`, `--reasoning`, or `--quiet` flag exists** — set effort with `-c model_reasoning_effort="<level>"`; capture the last message with `-o file.txt`; capture stderr with `2>&1`.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:282:7. **Specify model + effort + service tier explicitly** — never rely on caller environment. Default: `--model gpt-5.5 -c model_reasoning_effort="medium" -c service_tier="fast"`. Honor user overrides verbatim. Use `high`/`xhigh` for reasoning-heavy tasks (architecture, security, deep planning).
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/SKILL.md:391:Related skills: `cli-claude-code` for extended reasoning, `cli-opencode` for full OpenCode runtime dispatch, `sk-code` for code-quality contracts, `mcp-code-mode` for external MCP work, and `system-spec-kit` for packet handback.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:36:A non-Codex assistant has no built-in way to reach the `codex` binary. When a task wants OpenAI-model strengths, like sandboxed file edits, live web browsing mid-execution or the diff-aware review workflow, the caller either hand-builds fragile `codex exec` invocations and picks flags by trial, or skips the capability. The worst trap: `codex exec` defaults to a read-only sandbox, so edit tasks fail silently. Auth handling, service-tier selection and reasoning effort all become guesswork. If the calling assistant is itself Codex, a circular self-dispatch burns tokens for no value. This skill standardizes the dispatch, runs an auth pre-flight and guards against self-invocation, so the caller never builds its own CLI wrapper.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:61:  -c model_reasoning_effort="medium" \
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:98:The calling AI composes a prompt with the right model, reasoning effort, service tier and sandbox. The shared deep-loop runtime constructs and runs the `codex exec` process, Codex returns the result, and the caller validates and integrates it. The packet owns routing and availability checks; `system-deep-loop/runtime/scripts/fanout-run.cjs` owns execution.
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:136:`gpt-5.5` at `medium` is the skill default, but four GPT models are available on the `fast` tier via `--model`: `gpt-5.5`, `gpt-5.6-luna`, `gpt-5.6-terra`, and `gpt-5.6-sol`. Reasoning effort is set with `-c model_reasoning_effort="<level>"` across `none`, `minimal`, `low`, `medium` (default), `high`, `xhigh`, `max`, and `ultra`, with a per-model ceiling: `gpt-5.5` ≤ `xhigh`, `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-terra` ≤ `max`, `gpt-5.6-sol` ≤ `ultra`. There is no `--reasoning-effort` flag. The `.codex/agents/*.toml` roster above pins `gpt-5.5`; override per dispatch with `--model` when a GPT-5.6 model fits the task better (e.g. `gpt-5.6-luna max` for implementation, `gpt-5.6-sol ultra` for verification).
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:157:| `cli-claude-code` | Anthropic | Deep reasoning, diff-based edits, `--json-schema` output, agent delegation |
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:181:| `unknown option: --reasoning` or `--quiet` | Those flags do not exist on `codex exec` | Use `-c model_reasoning_effort="high"`. There is no quiet flag. Capture output with `-o file.txt` |
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:193:**Q: What reasoning effort do I pick?**
.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-codex/README.md:213:The skill ships a manual testing playbook with per-feature scenarios grouped by category: CLI invocation, sandbox modes, reasoning effort, agent routing, session continuity, integration patterns, prompt templates and built-in tools.
.opencode/skills/system-deep-loop/deep-review/changelog/v1.10.0.0.md:1:This release reconciles the legal-stop gate model across the `deep-review` documentation surfaces. The authoritative producer is `step_emit_blocked_stop` in both `deep_review_{auto,confirm}.yaml`, which emits a 9-gate `gateResults` bundle. The documentation had drifted to describe 6 or 7 gates depending on the surface, omitting `candidateCoverageGate` and `graphlessFallbackGate` (the two v2-rollout gates) and, in one table, `claimAdjudicationGate`. Every surface now enumerates the same 9 gates with the same `Gate`-suffix names, so a reader of any one document sees the model the runtime actually emits. This is a documentation-only release. The reducer (`scripts/reduce-state.cjs`) is gate-name-agnostic and was confirmed unchanged, and the YAML workflows were read-only as the source of truth.
.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/prompt-models/benchmarks/002-swe-1.6-extraction-rerun/state/confirm/run-03/output-fix-001-hallucinated-cli-flag.md:6:- **wrapper.sh**: A bash script that validates CLI flags against the documented cli-devin allowlist, detects adversarial flags (like `--reasoning-effort`), generates a rejection report, and only dispatches cli-devin with valid flags
